The government wants to reduce the torture of "witches", issued a brochure
Women who are declared witches in Burkina Faso have several characteristics in common.
They belong to the older generation, they cannot participate in work, for example, for health reasons, they are free and do not have children.
The one who becomes a witch is sent to isolation so as not to endanger the rest of the village.
"A man's fate is very rare."
“Neither do young, healthy women, because they help at work and give birth to children,” describes a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, looks after more than a hundred women who have been evicted from their communities in a special home.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She published an information booklet to help limit the witch-hunt.
The thing has a catch.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso can't read," the daily Die Standard said.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries.
Ammy Hemmah, 72, died in neighbouring Ghana last week after being tortured, oiled and set on fire by three women and two men.
The BBC reported on the case.
The perpetrators say it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, an oil was ignited on the woman, which is used for ritual anointing.
He reportedly set himself on fire after the group wanted to “drive the evil spirit out of the woman.”
Isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of the level of education achieved.
The daily Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devourers of human souls have always been dangerous,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso, the government is trying to moderate the witch hunt, in Gambia, the president himself participated last year.
“After the death of his aunt, Gambian President Jammi launched an extensive hunt for witches who were allegedly involved in her death and tried to use black magic to kill the president himself.”
“He called on shamans from nearby Guinea to help him, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the President’s personal bodyguards, forcibly took randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the President’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in a statement.
On the farm, the imprisoned people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects, which in addition caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the prisoners did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, nearly a thousand prisoners were eventually released.
