An elderly man stepped out of the door of the client center of the company RPG Byty "uhlobarona" Zden<0xC4><0x9B>k Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
He carried a file under his arm and a new lease on three apartments: his own, his daughter's and his son's, who is in prison.
All three of them have just been deregulated to raise rent.
Instead of 3500 per month, the son will pay CZK 4100 for a 2+1 apartment of the second category from next year.
"And that's not hot water, and the petrama must be melted," the man points out with a finger in his son's new contract, which he has full authority to sign.
"But I signed it," he explains, half angry and half resigned.
The civic association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new lease terms "irrelevant and immoral," advises tenants not to sign the new contract and wait until December 7, when it will publish instructions on how to act against them.
But the man just waved his hand.
"One says it, the other says it," he frowns.
