There is also a kindergarten in the office, the architects understood.
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect that she also hides a mini-schoolgirl with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by children of Arch.Design employees.
The architectural design company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings emerged, has been counting on space for its corporate mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
She employs almost 90 people, mostly in the age of the baby boomer, and she wanted women designers and architects to be able to return to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of reduced working hours, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of a social program.
Thus, builders and architects have the opportunity to combine a demanding job with child care.
The mini-school was invented by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of the management they managed to get a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the grant funding (a grant of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and ensure qualified staff and operation for two years.
After the financial subsidy has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to run the mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The preparation of the project took one year and the application for a subsidy was significantly helped by Economy Rating.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the nurse and the kindergarten teacher take care of the children all day, so children without age restrictions can go to kindergarten, but most of them are over 3 years old.
Because it is a "mini-college", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day, more of them are replaced.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation to school benches, English is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and there are no stressful situations with delayed pick-up of children from kindergartens distant from the parents’ workplace.
In this way, parents use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that there is a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship here.
Arch.Design has thus become one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look into the interiors by Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouth.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
From the locals, the house, thanks to its organic shapes, earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s secession.
The front of the house is played out by dream lines, gentle colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
With detailed observation, geometricity, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order can be seen.
At night, the entire facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of colors is even enhanced.
The winding and twisting of shapes equally occurs in interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepholes and moldings.
Batll<0xC3><0xB3> House, located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA0>cia No. 43, was built in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building an entirely new one, but soon accepted Gaudi’s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated with him.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
Many other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
Working together on the designs of Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> started a successful collaboration between Jujol and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s Casa Milá and G<0xC3><0xBC>ell Park, which contains Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s other works.
From the locals, the house soon after its completion, thanks to its organic shapes, earned the nickname "House of Bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening windows, began to call it the "causing house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of Saint George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed for his time a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree slope.
When creating Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of that time and did not let himself be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he received a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, during the completion, the city council was appalled by the result and asked for correction.
The councillors, for example, objected to the fact that the building interfered with the pillar and the public sidewalk.
The correction never happened, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the call of the city district, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> applied for (and successfully obtained) a permit to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a lounge and on the third floor there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented jewelry.
The entire six-storey house intersects the stairs, which can be climbed up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon door, and a larger company can comfortably communicate with each other without maintaining the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, the house with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s reconstruction also received an unusual roofing and two additional floors.
Impressive is Gaudi’s play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which is lined with the inner courtyard, and skylights.
The play of two colors gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and luxurious apartment is made available to the public.
The owners decided for this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They insisted on the tours because they found that it was a very advantageous business and in addition, they expanded the tours to include common and attic spaces, including a roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is certainly not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The sum far exceeds the price of admission to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of a house with dragon towers, you need to quickly make friends with one of the tenants and visit him directly at home.
How to choose a mattress and grate: women have different requirements than men
Not the sumptuous frame of the bed, but the quality of the lying area, that is, the mattress and the grate, give the foundation to a really good bed.
However, it must be harmoniously supplemented to suit a particular user.
When choosing, a lot of things decide, from weight, height, age, health and gender of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and grate are taken.
Typical example?
For example, latex mattresses are not suitable for weekend cottages, where they do not heat regularly, because they "warm up" more slowly.
In addition, they have a significantly higher weight than a standard polyurethane mattress.
However, it is necessary to rotate them regularly.
If they do not have a lot of vents in the core, and still lie on a solid plate, they retain moisture: mold could also appear under them.
It is also a matter of custom when choosing.
Those who have spent a long time abroad, where a lot of high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel good on a low and hard surface.
“Maybe all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they wouldn’t sleep here.”
"They needed a mattress with a softening layer of lazy foam on their battered shoulders, heels, and hips."
"These are recommended even for people with diabetes who have a disorder of the nervous system, so they poorly absorb 'information' from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, as well as other customers, were looking for a mattress with lazy foam years ago.
"Today it's cool, suitable mattress has Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico."
You don't have to be an NHL fighter to appreciate lazy foam.
This "miracle" works simply.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape according to the heat absorbed, or adapts to your warm body.
Nothing is forcing you, at night you will not roll over like after a hard match.
You just sleep better.
Lazy foam also acts as a protection against bedsores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of the foot to its height, which is usually about 21 to 34 cm.
A man and a woman with a height of about 180 cm need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be at the double bed 90 cm, total therefore 180 cm.
For single beds, for example for singles, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For convenience and possible visit.
"Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly bent at the elbow," advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, a guildmaster of the Upholstery and Decorators Guild, who has been dealing with the issue of healthy sleeping and furniture ergonomics for many years and has been lecturing it at vocational schools.
For a double, each needs its own grid and mattress, but here be careful when buying to sweeten the heights of the mattresses.
Otherwise, you will have no choice but to mount the grids to different heights, but you may not succeed with each frame of the bed.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a spring frame of at least 15, of which at least three centimeters count on the molding and budding layer.
"When you touch your hands or sit on a mattress, you should definitely not feel the springs," says Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of grate.
Full-fledged beds, where the mattresses and the base are like fused Siamese twins, have nothing to do in the bedrooms.
Mattresses are poorly ventilated, their cover cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And since we usually sweat 0.2 to 0.75 l per night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will start to resemble one large (and clogged) screen.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans about the life of mattresses up to 25 years, or even a lifetime guarantee.
But everything has its ales.
That’s why the advice from dealers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, do not give up hygiene and washable coating, but rather add a mattress protector that you can easily remove and wash.
Although today mattress covers are commonly made with zippers around the perimeter, so after opening we get two parts (for washing and the size of the washing machine is very important!), yet the manipulation in larger types (and in one person) when shooting could resemble a duel of light weight in the ring with heavy.
Do you have a solid board in your bed instead of a grid?
Never! Never!
Maximum for a bed intended for one night visits.
However, provide the board (if it does not already have them) with ventilation holes and use a mattress with a spring frame and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (including Taschenfederkern) and a budding layer.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a base.
For non-positioning lamellae with 14 to 18 lamellae, latex or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable, but you always pay for the grids with a larger number of lamellae, 28 or more, where the lamellae in the thigh area are doubled and their stiffness can be adjusted.
Positioning slats do not include mattresses with a spring frame, because they do not respond to positioning.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the slats, you can also indulge in the so-called shoulder cradle.
It is a special fastening of the slats, which allows you to push or even tilt the slat so that the sleeper's shoulder is nicely "buried".
For men who have "shoulders all over their backs", definitely an important thing.
Even mattress manufacturers remember it, who in the "gentleman's" began to use the softening zone precisely in the shoulder area.
They also remember women - they give them a softer surface in places of the hips.
For the most demanding customers are designed wing or plate gratings with the so-called multi-torsion suspension.
The pressure is distributed to several points and the tension is reduced.
However, beware, as soon as you use the wrong pillow (large and "pumpy") on the right mattress and grate, most of the "plus" will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and with the tips to reach only to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
As a suitable size, it is recommended 50 x 60 cm, which is preferred, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should align (along with the shoulder cradle grate or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original grass-filled straw mattresses.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least additives.
The trend is also in the bio mattress.
Raw materials from oil, from which polyurethane foams are produced, are replaced by natural oils, for example, from hops and soybeans.
Soybean is used by all known manufacturers.
"Bio in mattresses means that the core is made of a material of pure natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers, one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules to release the fresh smell of the forest or lavender.
There is also a division for men and women.
While men "cool" the plant extract of birch, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women, on the contrary, the covers "melt".
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making the weaker sex warmer.
Today's favourites?
A mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with a broken cell structure, it is more breathable than ordinary polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
By combining different stiffnesses of cold foam and "lazy" foam, multi-zone mattresses are created, which know exactly where the head, thighs and heels should be.
For a quality mattress you will pay from seven thousand crowns and above.
Those that meet health parameters, have a lower VAT rate, are taken as medical aids.
In the Czech Republic, Gumotex was the first to achieve this advantage.
Saving on the mattress and grate is not easy.
Sometimes you can use, for example, the actions of manufacturers or sellers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattress with memory foam Memory in the cover for 11 990 crowns.
The second one can be purchased for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cell structure and high density was started by Tempur material at a "cosmic" pace.
It was originally created as a material for NASA, because the astronauts were exposed to enormous overload during the launches.
Tempur softens in the heat, on the contrary, it hardens in the cold.
It adapts perfectly to the warm human body and distributes its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal against the formation of bedsores, but also for increasing comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only on mattresses, but also on medical products, for example, on special pillows under the feet, which lighten the legs and venous system.
Domestic manufacturers use, for example, Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
Tracking devices want more and more parents to watch their children
Fear of owning a child leads more and more people to the idea of babysitting via GPS.
The system originally created for searching for cars can also monitor the movement of people, and thus help in such cases as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anika Janatková.
The device is still about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can be as big as a watch.
A number of people were frightened by the case of the missing Anika and began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy happening," says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance devices to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases, such devices can be misused, for example, if they are put in a bag by someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"For the most part, customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know for what purpose the "box" is used and how it is used in the event of an emergency.
