But only about half of those polled in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas, are convinced Democrats, which pulls down the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, this is the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, it is a big increase (Figure 3).
About 34% said they trust the parliament in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same figures as last year, but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis in Latin America undermined democracy.
