Arsenic-resistant microbes increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the space to search for new forms of life on Earth and possibly beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth and claim that it is a sign that life has possibilities beyond the main elements that have been considered so far and basic.
"This organism has a dual capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or arsenic."
"This fact is very strange, but it is not evidence that this is some form of truly 'alien' life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time it was considered necessary for life six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, scientists have found that the bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after phosphorus is replaced by arsenic.
“You’ll start to wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
This finding is significant for the search for life beyond Earth, because researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report on the news published to discuss it, which did not reveal details of the find, has sparked widespread speculation on the internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It's not like that.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to exploit other elements that drive biochemistry, and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the substitution of one element by another element in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't an accidental find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she thought that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to replace one another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, it is very difficult for organisms to separate these elements."
"However, arsenic is so different that it does not work as well as phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it begins to work in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFOJ-1 and expose them to an increasing concentration of arsenic, which bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better when exposed to phosphorus, but because they can also survive with arsenic replacement, there is an increasing possibility that a form of life that uses arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced by phosphorus, is not new, but there has never been an example on which this fact could be proved.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that earlier life forms might have used it.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
