Prosecutors won't charge Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors cleared Senator John Ensign of a criminal charge related to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure a lobby, the senator's lawyers said on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat that Mr. Ensign, a Nevada Republican, faced and who was, until the time of the scandal, considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012. His affair made national headlines and damaged his career.
Mr Ensign's office said he was "certainly pleased" by the decision, which followed almost a year of investigation.
A senator could still face disciplinary proceedings before the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department "has informed us that Senator Ensign will no longer be the target of the investigation and that there are no plans to bring further charges against him in this matter."
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The decision came as a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Justice Department, who claimed there was strong evidence that Mr. Ensign was preparing to violate the federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents published in the October 2009 New York Times reported that Mr. Ensign was helping Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure a lucrative lobby that would lead to the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator’s relationship with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer in the Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political backers to find work for Mr. Hampton and supported their views after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, so many documents and interviews have been cited.
Since Hampton was until recently an assistant to Mr. Ensign, he was legally barred from lobbying his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts say the unusual settlement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared to be in violation of the lobbying ban.
From the evidence that was released, “it turned out to be a clear case of preparation for a violation of the law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington-based lawyer who specializes in defending clients being investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasoning behind the Ensign decision, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department was cautious about political lawsuits after a large number of failures, including last year's decision to suspend the lawsuit against former Senator Ted Stevens amid doubts over the indictment.
Federal prosecutors “clearly hid the guns,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that filed several complaints against Ensign.
“It basically shows that high-ranking government officials are not subject to the law,” she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s chief lawyer, said in an interview that he received a call from the DOJ prosecutor on Monday and then the next day, telling him that the DOJ had found no charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defence team is working with prosecutors to try to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in Wednesday's statement, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments which he had submitted to the public prosecutors.
“I’m not comfortable sharing the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice except that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to stop investigating a separate complaint in which an ethics group filed charges that Ensign’s parents’ payment of $96,000 to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that money meant anything other than a gift.
One company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work was NV Energy, a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator.
One December 2008 email showed that after Mr. Hampton began to act as a lobbyist in the company, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, communicated with Mr. Hampton and told him that he had "banged" at the Department of the Interior regarding the subject under discussion.
Mr. Ensign also attended lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and called on the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after they hired Mr. Hampton for lobbying work.
When the news of the affair first surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After months of stagnation, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
In a report that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of an investigation into the crime, his spokesman Jennifer Cooper said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department and end the entire investigation.
"Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the Nevada people," she said.
Cheshire's appeal goes viral on Twitter
There were half a dozen of them in the courtroom.
Minute by minute, they were sending messages about the horrific testimony via Twitter.
Finally, the defense says that more than 140,000 Twitter messages dealt with raping and tying children to beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of killing three Cheshire, Connecticut, family members, was scheduled to officially end with the death penalty, for which the jury voted.
But Mr. Hayes's lawyers have already filed an appeal with the court with requests and arguments that the court would likely have employed for years.
One of the most provocative is that the intense reporting of the process – including the widespread use of Twitter by mainstream reporters – created a “circus atmosphere” and this widespread, immediate penetration of information with disturbing details then led the jury to make a decision in the sense of influencing public opinion.
This claim could force the judge to consider whether, with the advent of new technologies, they should also require new rules in the courtroom.
“As I have experienced in this trial, I think there is a real danger that the incorporation of new technologies in the courtroom affects the rights of a fair trial for individuals,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, Hayes’s chief counsel.
The trial’s judge, Jon C. Blue of the state’s top court, briefly rejected the claims regarding last week’s ruling, saying the media was “carefully controlled” and that there was no evidence to suggest the jury acted under public influence.
But this is probably not the last word in this case.
For decades, courts have recognized that reporting notorious cases can raise questions about the fairness of the process.
In a 1966 court order, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of Cleveland chiropractor Dr. Sam Sheppard for the murder of his wife, saying in its ruling that in the case of Sheppard versus Maxwell, the trial was due to the media’s “carnival atmosphere.”
Some believe that this crime was the inspiration for the TV show and the film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers said that the courts of appeal, which reviewed Hayes’s verdict half a century later, might be surprised to find that new rules determining the manner of communication from the courtrooms might be necessary, which was unimaginable in Dr. Sheppard’s case.
“There’s a general reason to worry about the impact of new media” in highly watched cases, said John J. Donohue III, a Stanford Law School professor who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that said it was being practiced arbitrarily.
Professor Donohue said some judges may be interested in the idea that restricting direct communication from courtrooms could make the process fairer.
The Twitter case is just one of many outlined by Mr. Hayes’s lawyers who would have been able to argue for years to delay the execution of the sentence.
Advocates also argue, for example, that Mr. Hayes may have been prejudiced by Judge Blue’s refusal to allow him to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them horrific crime photos when choosing a jury.
Some of the jurors said they were horrified by the photos of the victims, who became Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Advocates say they will also reject the constitutionality of the death penalty, arguing that the judge wrongly dismissed a juror who was critical of prosecutors and that his decision wrongly put more pressure on the verdict and directed the jury to think over the weekend.
The jurors were not separated.
But their arguments about the impact of the scope of the process may attract the most interest.
They said in an objection to last month’s verdict that the case dominated news in Connecticut and was discussed during the campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media was constantly fanning the flames of emotion about the case.
“The daily rush of media, cameras and reporters to court,” the lawyer wrote, “was something that has not yet been seen here in New Haven and may also be a national rarity.”
Their focus on the impact of Twitter is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists claimed that the immediate reporting was more outrageous than the reports reported later, and from their point of view, the judicial police should control the scope of other trials.
But some lawyers have demanded courts of appeal with frequently used arguments that social and technological changes require court adjustments.
Mr. Hayes' lawyers are pursuing this right.
In their archives, they referred to the Supreme Court’s 1966 ruling on Dr. Sheppard’s case because of the breadth of the trial and wanted to clarify the requirement that new media require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the Sheppard versus Maxwell case of the 21st century."
Can politeness overcome a precipice?
After a campaign that was notable for its insulting and negativism, a small amount of politeness appeared in Washington this week.
Is this the first swallow of real cooperation between two political parties or just an illusory moment before a quick return to the party struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and parliamentary leaders did not yield any major breakthroughs on the major issues that need to be discussed during the session.
In any case, however, it was a polite discussion dealing with the differences of opinion between the two parties, as well as defining their common responsibilities, rather than another empty episode of partisan struggle.
Wednesday's public meeting of the president's deficit committee was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that close cooperation over several months has built mutual respect that goes beyond the ideological divide that still divides members.
And it is quite difficult to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
The two sides are now in a probationary period - probing each other for signs of collegiality and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and electoral patience towards a renewed party war.
Therefore, the Tuesday meeting and its subsequent evaluation by the participants were also carried out with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too wide and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the conditions that have prevailed here for the last two years.
Whether it’s about taxes, spending, health care, or rights, both sides are miles away.
However, the November elections were prepared by Washington at least quickly.
“It’s not a question of whether regulatory matters have changed,” said Pete Wehner, Bush’s administrator, now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“It’s inevitable after the election.
The elections stirred up the emotions of the party members, and they then fell silent.
It's good."
On a number of issues, particularly those to be discussed at the meeting, Republicans and Democrats have little chance of finding a solution.
Bush’s tax cut expired at the end of the year, and no one sees it as favorable.
Both sides want to find a way to protect some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, the likely compromise on unemployment benefits is only because Republicans cannot see how they support tax cuts for the wealthy, while the unemployed are denied unemployment benefits.
After Tuesday's White House meeting, there is already greater optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of a new opening treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution points out that successful cooperation on crucial issues will not necessarily lead to a relationship between the two political parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable, he said.
“After the things are done that need to be done, psychology will return to one of the confrontations in the short term,” he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism - which is largely widespread - that politeness will lead to genuine cooperation.
“I look at all the events between now and 2012 as a shadow box, when the main events will take place in 2012,” he said.
The reasons are largely due to the formation of a new Republican majority in the White House and the voters of the tea parties that helped create it.
Republican leaders now face the danger of exaggeration, knowing that they must act on their promises and cut government spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan lines are clear in the initial reactions to the deficit recommendations, which include reform of the tax code and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Joint chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and are, in their view, to push the deficit issue to the public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in an 18-member committee to present their plan as an official recommendation and fight to get as close to that number as possible.
The greatest resistance is among elected officials on the jury who suggest that in the case of financial issues, at least today, we have little basis or will for compromise.
Galston predicts two stages in the battles between the White House and the parliamentary Republicans.
The first will begin next year in the form of party conflicts, with Republicans calling on Obama to address budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater party cooperation.
What causes the shift?
Public opinion.
There is a lot of evidence that despite the partisanship in the last election, most Americans want to continue to see two parties working together.
If it could be aimed at the heel, as it was in 1995, then both sides will be watching the public’s reaction very closely.
Anyone at risk of losing votes is likely to change course and seek compromise.
This can be an optimistic view of the matter.
The partisanship and directionality is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and it turns out that there is a greater ideological divide between Obama and the parliamentary Republicans than there was between the Republicans and Bill Clinton.
At the same time, activists on both sides see 2010 as a prelude to more important elections in 2012.
Based on this reality, the courtesy that emerged this week would have been welcomed by many Americans.
But it will cost a lot of effort on both sides to find common ground on issues that still divide them.
A leaked U.S. documentary portrays Moscow as a haven of corruption
The management of the city is in the hands of a “kleptocracy” and it continues to be a part of the bribes and bribes for protection that come on the way to the Kremlin, the US embassy in Russia said in February’s records.
Both the police and the Federal Security Service are largely holding the protective wings that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They collect money not only from legal transactions but also from organized criminal groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy – which Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical of the office” – will take its toll as the money starts to move up the ladder.
The recording, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted via WikiLeaks on their website on Wednesday.
The record is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
The record was written at a time when the mayor was still Yuri Luzhkov and accuses him of a large share of corruption.
He was recalled in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but since then we can only observe minimal changes in the purge.
Luzhkov and his wife Yelena Baturina, who owns a prominent design firm, have consistently denied corruption charges for many years, and have won several lawsuits for falsely accusing him of such allegations.
In September, he told a Russian TV station when asked about the proven evidence of corruption: “It’s crazy, it’s dirt, it’s dirt.”
The Russians believe with absolute conviction that if their society is corrupt, it will turn out to be a vote.
However, it is unusual to encounter such details in such a way, in an embassy report, and it is also unheard of for diplomats from foreign countries to do so.
“The Moscow city government and its association with criminal elements have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional,’ and confirm that the government functions more as a kleptocracy than as a government,” the report says.
“Criminal elements enjoy the so-called ‘krysha’ (a term from the world of crime and the mafia, which literally means ‘roof’ or protection) provided by the police, the Federal Security Service, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior and the Prosecutor’s Office, as well as everywhere in the government bureaucracy of the city of Moscow.
"Analytics has identified a three-tiered structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the very top."
"Federal Security Service, Department of the Interior and Militia are on the second level."
"Finally, at the lowest level are common criminals and corrupt inspectors."
“It’s an inefficient system where criminal groups fill in the blanks in some areas because the city doesn’t provide some services.”
The report says the FSB is taking money from the biggest companies and the police are targeting smaller businesses.
One source said, "shopkeepers in Moscow are aware that it is better to get protection from the FSB or the Ministry of the Interior (rather than from organized criminal groups), since they do not only have more weapons, resources and force than criminal groups, but are also protected by law."
"For this reason, protection from criminal gangs is no longer on course."
The record says that while the withdrawal of money is complex, the protection itself may already be in trouble; even those who pay may sometimes be arrested.
For those who do not pay fast enough, their stores are closed under various pretexts.
