"The truth about the whole thing is that it is about our mutual cooperation, which is an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he said.
"But to be honest, we didn't think it would be done with such arrogance, with such pressure, you know, so unethical."
Veterans of the Khmer Rouge are forced to deal with the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom with dirty and peeled walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who had built it, the leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves that Moka."
"He was a good leader and took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as the “butcher” for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander in this remote Khmer Rouge state in northwestern Cambodia remains popular, where he has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge relinquished power, long-standing loyalty is also broken in Anlong Veng.
In April, victims at the Truth and Reconciliation Forum were allowed to publicly confront people who were part of the regime.
In June, the government provided textbooks explaining the history of the Khmer Rouge and its former soldiers to children for the first time.
And in July, together with the UN and the Cambodian court, to bring the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, the sentencing of the former leader, notoriously violent association Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Ghost, to 35 years in prison.
With each such advance, there was growing unrest among Khmer Rouge veterans in Anlong Veng, complicating efforts at reconciliation and their attempts to re-engage in Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, head of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization that examines the regime.
"For them, life among the Khmer Rouge was beautiful, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It divides families."
During the Khmer Rouge regime in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its soldiers fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they began an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary waged guerrilla wars from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement, the country was led to the first democratic elections in 1993. Large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to move to a government that culminated in the capitulation of Ieng Sara in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who persevered, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters have fallen into ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgic for the time of the movement.
Although several elite Khmer Rouge have maintained their local government position in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak, like unskilled farmers.
"These people have only benefited minimally from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums across Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are surrounded by the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They were brought up with no idea of doing business."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling as a poor farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
'That Mok has fed them all.'
"But life is hard now, because we have to do everything ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge court has also raised concerns.
Early next year, the court will begin investigating Nuon Che, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court has a mandate to prosecute the leading offenders and the people responsible for the crimes, but it has not been said whether it will continue in the four cases.
There was little to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has centered on Im Chaema, 64, who was a regional leader in Banteay Meanchey Province during the Khmer Rouge's rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Documentation Centre in Cambodia that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project likely to have killed thousands of forced laborers.
Last night, Im Chaem returned from work in the field to her wooden house on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun began to descend and shadows appeared across the arid grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about her past among the Khmer Rouge.
If the court had called her, she would have refused to go.
"There is peace and stability in Cambodia," she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned of instability if the court searches for other suspects, though experts and historians disagree.
"Cambodia must dig a deep hole and bury the past in it," he said.
But confronting the past is just what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
"Reconciliation in Khmer means gluing broken pieces together," he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand each other."
The Centre published the first textbook approved by the Khmer Rouge government, 75 pages long and entitled "History of Democratic Cambodia."
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as an addition to the Ministry of Education’s history textbook, which contains fewer than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
Like many people in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng knew little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s connection to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a high school student in Anlong Veng said the new textbook helps students understand important parts of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he took home a book to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the courts," he said.
"They're suspicious because they're not sure how many people the court will prosecute."
Such resistance makes the reconciliation process more complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, textbooks and the court are starting to have an impact, he said.
The Khmer Rouge still have a strong charm here.
Up in the Dangrek Mountains, the path is overgrown with weeds and littered with discarded plastic bags, leading to a rectangle of black soot covered with a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a mobile phone salesman on the side of the road, said she didn't know much about the man who was cremated at the scene.
"But he has a strong spirit, a lot of local people come and pray to him," she said.
Nuom Sothea had a birthday and planned to visit the Pol Pot resting place later, where she would bring a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope that it would bring her luck.
