Zapatero and the Red German Line
Berlin decided to keep the euro, but set the conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets have provoked a dual government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero has proposed new adaptation measures, ranging from tax cuts for small and medium-sized enterprises, through the regulation of private intermediary agencies or the abolition of 426 euros for the unemployed without benefits, to the privatisation of 49% of AENA (Spanish airports and air traffic control), the manager of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of the state.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgadová, with the support of former Prime Minister Felipe González, joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel over her responsibility for unleashing the current crisis.
How to interpret these movements?
Let us say in advance that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here, Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which alludes to the idea of adhering to the old traditions that a large part of the other members hold.
In the face of European resistance, there is speculation in Germany about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first of these is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also, for example, Austria or the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the brand - although now it may seem like a scifi, this version has wide public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is to rework the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, budgetary austerity, fines for guilty states, possible deferrals of payments for some of them, and to extend the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for spins now.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission instigated deficits in 2009, the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany considered to be right (fiscal austerity and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second was shown by this Central European country, when Merkel painfully prolonged the decision to save Greece.
Even then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly opposed to the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel reappeared with a clear position when she called for the reform of the European Union's conventions so as to enable the rescue of a Member State and at the same time for private creditors to be obliged to bear part of the costs.
This opinion was interpreted as anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat lenient form, has been approved, and in the coming months we should be following the Union's reform process, which should make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although measures now need to be taken, with which they seem to disagree too much, from this date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary zone, in which rule-breaking states will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to declare payment deferrals, and the private sector will also have to bear some of the costs.
Germany suggests to us that we must take a strict path of growth with increased savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
They simply do not tolerate another option based on receivables and build-up, with the huge balance-of-payments gaps that prevailed during Spain’s booming growth years.
The offer is clear.
And we'd make a mistake if we didn't understand.
It is not just a question of restoring the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want us to do is much harder.
And the worst thing is that under these conditions, we could be wrong ourselves.
I hope that these current turbulences will replace more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunity they give us until the spring of 2013.
Prime Minister Zapatero seems to have understood this as well, and his double statement (reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big business and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the way has opened up to the idea that things need to be put in order.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it does not seem to want to move with it.
And it cannot be ruled out that leaving a eurozone full of not-so-serious countries is one of the options that can be considered.
Well, Germany will always be able to tell us that it warned us.
Sport and circumvention of rules
The feints shown by Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax show wit, not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November caused a sea of ink to be written about whether this is or is not unsportsmanlike behavior, and whether, eventually, UEFA should punish both players.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which had their team clearly won) the appointed players one by one deliberately lost time at the moment when the foul was due to be played, in order to provoke the referee, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in their group lead - and will be able, deprived of cards, to continue to the next stage.
In the end, the disciplinary committee of UEFA awarded coach José Mourinho a two-game penalty and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, rules that are unwritten but followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that the Real Madrid team (which boasts nobility and honor in its anthem, and which has already fined its player for similar acts), and apparently also due to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history as a comedian and provocateur.
In any event, the debate is about whether this type of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts circumvent the law; they are indeed actions which respect the rules of sport, but whose meaning they seem to be trying to circumvent.
It is decided what type of damage such actions do to the sports spirit.
One of the features of sports behavior is the physical inviolability of opponents, which was not violated in these cases, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these features characterizing clean play is to avoid that players have an advantage over the opposing team due to their offense - which also did not happen here.
Thus, paradoxical to the action of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as a ruse or circumvention of the law did not occur, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should have been as obvious as possible in order to receive punishment.
They waited and were happy to be punished.
Another question, however, is what advantage the guilty will have from their intentional wrongdoing.
Here it should be noted that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that in the current match will not achieve any benefit, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And even this is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in a future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by this action, the players will receive a penalty, and move to the second round of cards, in which one card less than in the first round is enough to exclude.
So, as the rounds continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, well, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
In the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between wit and circumvention is not quite clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because these were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the transmission of instructions to provoke them from the leadership took place.
Damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
