The United States is changing its visa rules.
People will have to contact the Visa Applicants Service Centres before interviewing at the Consular Section; costs will be lower and waiting times will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Application Service Centres (ASC) before interviewing at the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will collect the biometric information of the applicant and will be evaluated by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, among which are the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay a fee for arranging the meeting, another for processing the application and another for delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant will pay only one fee, which will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only turn to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and be fingerprinted.
Since biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who request a second interview meeting at the Consular Section will spend a shorter time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
