World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
The United Nations has proposed a plan in Cancun to restore home, shop and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas effect (GES) limit that corresponds to nearly one-third of the additional limit to be achieved for stabilizing the planet’s climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n to compensate for the absence of hard-to-reach reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the hot bulbs that monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market are replaced with fluorescent bulbs or, better still, with light-emitting diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a significant amount of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet generated by lighting would be from.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world’s emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70% of the world’s car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will need to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance in order to achieve stabilization of climate warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to exclude that it does not get out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat, and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with new bulbs with DEL, we reduce this consumption by two more times.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new incandescent bulbs with DEL, such as those launched this week by Philips – this company reportedly participated in a UN study – have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a hot bulb, giving us an idea of possible savings with a replacement plan that would apply in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact light bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection facilities.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluocompact light bulb, but rather a thermal coal-fired power plant, which emits much of the mercury needed to produce electricity squandered in hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, they put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation each year.
The report also details the profits that each country would make from this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of a $3.5 billion thermal power plant.
