Vengeful Hackers and Causal Spies
The Wikileaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, an obvious scandal is revealed, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and anticipates a future dominated by regression.
But let's keep things in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press cuts.
Berlusconi’s “extraordinary revelations” about the way Americans live their lives reveal what everyone has been able to read for months in any newspaper (all but these two Berlusconi’s own), and Qaddafi’s infamous caricature profile has long been a subject for cabaret artists to sketch.
The rule that secret documents may consist only of reports already known is fundamental in the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a bookstore that deals with esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Masons) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
Not only because the author of occult texts does not like to search for new information (he does not even know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who are engaged in occultism believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have already learned.
That's Dan Brown's mechanism of success.
The same goes for secret documents.
The informant is a lazy, and lazy (or limited in spirit) head of the intelligence services (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, an editor in the newspaper Libération), who considers only what he admits to be true.
The highly classified information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to the State Department was the same that Newsweek had published a week earlier.
Why, then, was there so much confusion about the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II and since heads of state can make phone calls or fly to a joint dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation, have transformed into spy centers.
Any viewer watching films about the investigation knows very well that it is only out of hypocrisy that it is seemingly ignored.
However, the fact that this is being repeated in public dishonors the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can get the most top-secret information from the most powerful country in the world is a hard blow, not a negligible one, to the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victim and his "perpetrator".
But let's move on from here to the deep truth of what happened.
Once, in the days of Orwell, it was possible to contain all the power, like some Big Brother who controlled every movement of his people.
Orwell’s prophecy has been proven ever since, thanks to the ability to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, he became a citizen a total victim of the crown of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now, that even the "graves" with the most secret information of the powerful cannot resist the intervention of some hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker - elected as a citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can he hold on to a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that a true secret is a meaningless secret (and a meaningless secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious meaningless secret, because it is extracted from public life; but to reveal Clinton was, as WikiLeaks did, a meaningless secret.
WikiLeaks made no mistake about Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something great for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this blow to the established power so significant?
It is clear that in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - this would be equal to its publication on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is also quite obvious that with current technologies it is useless to hope that messages can be kept secret over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when the head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future?
I am well aware that for the time being my prognosis is science fiction and therefore fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials who are discreetly transporting formalities along uncontrolled routes and carrying only those messages that they know by heart or rather hide rare information in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be stored in unique copies in key-locked drawers: All in all, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways forward, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet rehabilitated the wire-based telegraph.
Videocassettes (analog) allowed cinema lovers to shoot a movie step by step, slide it back and forth and reveal all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (digital) allow only to jump through chapters, that is, through macros.
By high-speed trains we will reach Milan from Rome in three hours, while we need three and a half hours to travel by plane and transport, which includes.
It is not extraordinary, then, that politics and communication techniques will return to horse-drawn carriages.
One final note.
At other times, the press tried to understand what was being done in the secrecy of the embassy.
Now it is the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
