The European Union has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion for three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to funding a fast start: a report detailing the action of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation is invaluable and valued for its true value: developed countries and civil society would like to be treated equally and with the same degree of precision by all developed countries and civil society.
The EU announces that it released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to deliver on its promise of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, this funding is "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without harming public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million for three years to the title of fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment terms or with terms at the level of public development aid.
France, on the other hand, considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of the Public Development Assistance d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease), it is supposed to keep its commitment regarding the financing of "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 borrowed is equal to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be evidenced for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission reduction, consisting in more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we get as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it as the equivalent of our liabilities, but as the loan rate for the country (the rate of interest for the creditor).
But France can only give the following justification: it is "keeping" its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million, of which 91.5% is a loan (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>389.8 million) and 8.5% is a gift (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million) - see the EU document for yourself.
It is the only country in the European Union that uses a loan on such a scale.
Germany asked for 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) kept their commitments with 100% of the donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union gives <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfill its promise, France will give only 10 centimes and consider this effort comparable.
What a beautiful piece of juggling!
To sum up, in its "fast start" financing, France operates with double fraud: on the one hand with the development of the stock in time, and on the other with a real financial burden.
Despite spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, he can convince himself that he is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it was Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would member states continue donating when you only need to lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early funding is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not our case.
Whatever the case may be, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its accounting practices for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of compliance with its obligations and with decency and fairness vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing long-term financing deposits (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not avoid the question of "additionality" or the method of posting loans.
France should change its position in order to become as progressive in these deposits as in the others.
So everyone is putting their hope in the new environment minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who is coming to Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement of France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
Alarming about the pesticides children will ingest.
A 10-year-old child will one day ingest 81 different chemicals, according to one study published this Wednesday, from the Future Generations Association (ex-Rights and Preservation of Future Generations Movement).
The association, which notes that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the low number of samples analyzed, but are characteristic of the issue being processed," bought between July and September foods commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a snack for one child of about a decade in supermarkets.
These typical foods, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as confectionery, have been analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other polluting agents.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are carcinogenic, possible or likely, and five substances are bright carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptive to the endocrine glands (IBS), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
“While in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical ingested individually are not exceeded, in our research we see well that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking,” the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain in themselves about ten residuums with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil and reported as a small snack in a study, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, for which studies have found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, beefsteak from minced meat, tuna in a can, and even a bun and chewing gum were spiked with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
The salmon steak for dinner was the “richest” with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave did not avoid analysis.
"The ultimate risk to consumers of this 'contamination cocktail' is likely to be underestimated," the study said.
Ecological Europe-Greens (EE-LV) proposed "faced with an urgent situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop "the rise of civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
